"script": "A microwave can boil your coffee while the mug stays cool to the touch. So how does it cook food with no flame at all? Inside, a part called the magnetron fires invisible waves into the chamber, bouncing them off the metal walls. And these waves are tuned to hunt one thing: water molecules. They grab each tiny water molecule and flip it back and forth billions of times a second. Then all that frantic jiggling creates friction, and friction is just heat. This means your food is really cooking itself, from the water trapped inside it.",
